The Minister of Mines and Steel Development, Abubakar Bawa Bwari, has inaugurated a six-man ministerial committee for the rehabilitation of the Ladi Kwali Pottery Centre, Suleja. The minister who was represented by the Project Coordinator of the Mineral Sector Support for Economic Diversificstion (MinDiver) under the ministry, Mr. Linus Adie, said he was excited to be associated with the revival story of the famous Ladi Kwali Pottery Training Centre. “Our target is to recreate the glory of the past era and surpass it. The centre was regarded as a citadel of industry and technology where ordinary clay was transformed into aesthetic household wares. The centre attracted many visitors from all over the world. It brought the Nigerian local pottery industry to international fame, and to us, it stood as a symbol of industry,” he said. In a statement, the minister said the goal of the Federal Government was to restore the glory of the centre and that the first step in that direction was the inauguration of the steering committee to develop a strategy for the rehabilitation of the centre. He described the centre as a good example in achieving the lofty goals within the nation’s local industry when accomplished in view of the country’s current plan of diversifying the economy and creating employment opportunities for the huge population through the utilisation of local resources for industrial production. The committee has Engr. Sani Alhassan (chairman), Um Ladi Kwali Centre: A legacy in ruins The shell called Ladi Kwali Centre Remembering (Dr.) Hadiza Ladi Kwali, 29 years after Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin